snippet.textDisplay: Elderly beautiful lady in the music video is truly touching and adds a layer of depth to the narrative. Her resilience and warmth shine through despite the darkness surrounding her, both figuratively and literally. The scene where she mistakenly credits the singer for fixing the light, only to express her gratitude by gifting a flower, is incredibly poignant. It's a powerful reminder of how even in the midst of despair, kindness and connection can illuminate our paths. She symbolizes hope and the human capacity for compassion in the most unexpected moments. It's these nuanced characters that make the storytelling in this video so impactful and memorable.

snippet.textDisplay: This song had so much potential but it ultimately fell flat; Kaavish is its only saving grace. Jaffer Zaidi is a great lyricist and has an absolutely beautiful voice. His part should have been the chorus. However, Abdul Hannan had very unremarkable lyrics. I’ve listened to this song over five times and can’t remember a single line he sang. Coke Studio needs to onboard some professional lyricists to support the newer artists with mature songwriting. They need to do some homework by listening to older Pakistani or Bollywood ghazals and songs or even the odd recent song with poetry-worthy lyrics.  Moreover, Abdul Hannan has more monthly listeners than Kaavish, so it doesn’t make sense from any pov to give him the majority of this song.
